1
00:00:00,002 --> 00:00:03,218
Let's look at the script powering this
demo.

2
00:00:10,721 --> 00:00:14,945
The header sets output file, dimensions,
and voice.

3
00:00:19,653 --> 00:00:26,589
Here's the magic—the at-offscreen
directive. Everything below it runs but is
NOT recorded.

4
00:00:31,300 --> 00:00:39,052
This creates a terminal session called
joke one and echoes a dad joke. The viewer
never sees this happen.

5
00:00:43,764 --> 00:00:49,692
Same for joke two—another named session,
another joke, all invisible to the viewer.

6
00:00:54,400 --> 00:01:01,192
And joke three. Three terminal sessions,
three dad jokes, zero video footage.

7
00:01:05,906 --> 00:01:12,506
Then at-onscreen starts the recording.
From here on, everything goes into the
video.

8
00:01:17,330 --> 00:01:26,138
Later in the script, we switch back to
each joke terminal. The jokes are already
there—pre-loaded during offscreen setup.

9
00:01:30,483 --> 00:01:36,411
Joke one was set up offscreen. You never
saw it happen, but here it is.

10
00:01:39,723 --> 00:01:45,723
Joke two, same story. Prepared in advance,
revealed on cue.

11
00:01:49,043 --> 00:01:54,443
And joke three. All the setup happened
before you started watching.

12
00:01:54,884 --> 00:01:59,636
Offscreen directives let you prepare
everything before the camera rolls.

13
00:02:08,117 --> 00:02:16,637
Install dependencies, start servers,
pre-load pages—all invisible to viewers.
Welcome to cleaner demos.

